00:00:00.506 --> 00:00:09.976 A:middle
[ Silence ]

2
00:00:10.476 --> 00:00:12.556 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon, and welcome.

3
00:00:13.626 --> 00:00:14.136 A:middle
Thank you.

4
00:00:14.456 --> 00:00:15.696 A:middle
How's everybody doing?

5
00:00:16.566 --> 00:00:19.356 A:middle
It's been a fun week,
excellent, good.

6
00:00:19.666 --> 00:00:20.776 A:middle
I'm Gordie Freedman.

7
00:00:20.946 --> 00:00:25.746 A:middle
I work on UIKit, and
today we're going to talk

8
00:00:25.746 --> 00:00:28.516 A:middle
about State restoration on iOS.

9
00:00:29.486 --> 00:00:31.306 A:middle
So has this happened to you?

10
00:00:31.736 --> 00:00:35.536 A:middle
You're using an application,
you go to do something else,

11
00:00:35.966 --> 00:00:39.536 A:middle
and when you go back, the
application's lost your place.

12
00:00:40.476 --> 00:00:44.056 A:middle
Maybe you were typing something,
maybe you were reading something

13
00:00:44.056 --> 00:00:47.356 A:middle
and scrolled somewhere, but
the application went back

14
00:00:47.356 --> 00:00:48.046 A:middle
to the beginning.

15
00:00:48.576 --> 00:00:51.086 A:middle
In fact, maybe you don't really
remember what you were doing.

16
00:00:51.276 --> 00:00:53.696 A:middle
You were hoping the
application would remember.

17
00:00:54.296 --> 00:00:57.616 A:middle
And as developers, we
don't want this to happen

18
00:00:57.616 --> 00:00:59.236 A:middle
to the users of our apps.

19
00:00:59.746 --> 00:01:01.016 A:middle
It can be very frustrating.

20
00:01:01.626 --> 00:01:05.566 A:middle
But the good news is we've
got some really nice APIs

21
00:01:05.726 --> 00:01:08.886 A:middle
that make it very easy to
provide a seamless experience

22
00:01:09.116 --> 00:01:10.576 A:middle
when applications start back up.

23
00:01:11.096 --> 00:01:15.036 A:middle
I'm going to talk about
four things today.

24
00:01:16.036 --> 00:01:19.916 A:middle
First I'm going to go over a
small recap of the feature.

25
00:01:20.466 --> 00:01:22.056 A:middle
It's not a full review.

26
00:01:22.466 --> 00:01:26.626 A:middle
We did a session last year in
2012, and if you want to fill

27
00:01:26.626 --> 00:01:29.436 A:middle
in some of the gaps,
you can go watch that.

28
00:01:29.436 --> 00:01:31.566 A:middle
We also have some
documentation online,

29
00:01:31.936 --> 00:01:33.076 A:middle
and you can check that out.

30
00:01:33.566 --> 00:01:36.446 A:middle
But I think even if you're not
that familiar, you'll be able

31
00:01:36.446 --> 00:01:38.036 A:middle
to follow along just fine.

32
00:01:39.056 --> 00:01:43.206 A:middle
I'm going to focus a lot
on what's new in iOS 7.

33
00:01:43.396 --> 00:01:46.076 A:middle
We'll see what we've
added and how that plays.

34
00:01:46.616 --> 00:01:51.106 A:middle
We're going to talk a
little bit about security

35
00:01:51.326 --> 00:01:54.246 A:middle
and background operation --
couple of interesting topics

36
00:01:54.246 --> 00:01:55.506 A:middle
that I think we might want

37
00:01:55.506 --> 00:01:57.106 A:middle
to spend a little
time thinking about.

38
00:01:57.756 --> 00:02:01.276 A:middle
And then finally, I'm going
to go over some of the tools

39
00:02:01.276 --> 00:02:06.216 A:middle
that we have that can help you
to be able to both validate

40
00:02:06.216 --> 00:02:08.735 A:middle
that you're doing -- or your
app is doing what you expect,

41
00:02:09.485 --> 00:02:10.966 A:middle
and help diagnose problems.

42
00:02:11.526 --> 00:02:15.426 A:middle
So when we talk about
state restoration,

43
00:02:15.906 --> 00:02:16.996 A:middle
it's a simple idea --

44
00:02:17.776 --> 00:02:21.696 A:middle
one application to just go
back exactly where it was

45
00:02:21.966 --> 00:02:24.286 A:middle
so the user's experience
is not interrupted,

46
00:02:24.856 --> 00:02:26.926 A:middle
as if the application
had just been

47
00:02:26.926 --> 00:02:28.356 A:middle
in the background all the time.

48
00:02:28.946 --> 00:02:33.086 A:middle
And if the application exits and
restarts, the user won't know.

49
00:02:33.756 --> 00:02:37.346 A:middle
And it really is predicated
on how the user views this,

50
00:02:37.346 --> 00:02:39.726 A:middle
and we want to think a lot
about what the user's doing.

51
00:02:40.776 --> 00:02:42.456 A:middle
You want to look at
the different parts

52
00:02:42.456 --> 00:02:46.356 A:middle
of your application and
examine what you need to save

53
00:02:46.356 --> 00:02:47.596 A:middle
and what you need to restore.

54
00:02:47.906 --> 00:02:50.476 A:middle
And that's great, but
start at the top down.

55
00:02:50.806 --> 00:02:54.196 A:middle
Think about it as if you're
using the application and think,

56
00:02:54.196 --> 00:02:57.186 A:middle
"If I was using this and it
went away, where do I want it

57
00:02:57.186 --> 00:02:59.406 A:middle
to come back," and
then from there,

58
00:02:59.546 --> 00:03:01.756 A:middle
let that inform what
you save and restore.

59
00:03:02.306 --> 00:03:06.706 A:middle
I'm going to give a
short demo just to kind

60
00:03:06.706 --> 00:03:08.096 A:middle
of highlight what
I'm talking about.

61
00:03:08.206 --> 00:03:13.456 A:middle
So I've got a very
simple application,

62
00:03:13.656 --> 00:03:15.676 A:middle
got a collection
view, you can see,

63
00:03:15.826 --> 00:03:17.916 A:middle
do the nice collection
view layout stuff.

64
00:03:17.916 --> 00:03:20.496 A:middle
And I'm going to
scroll around and look

65
00:03:20.496 --> 00:03:22.796 A:middle
for an image that I want to see.

66
00:03:23.636 --> 00:03:26.086 A:middle
So these are all thumbnails
with little titles --

67
00:03:26.276 --> 00:03:27.356 A:middle
pretty standard stuff.

68
00:03:27.496 --> 00:03:29.436 A:middle
I'm going to select one --

69
00:03:29.536 --> 00:03:31.276 A:middle
you can see that I've got
the selection there --

70
00:03:31.276 --> 00:03:32.376 A:middle
let it roll in.

71
00:03:33.376 --> 00:03:36.336 A:middle
Let's make it a little
bigger so it's easier to see.

72
00:03:37.096 --> 00:03:41.716 A:middle
Maybe I'll even get rid of these
bars here and make it like that.

73
00:03:42.376 --> 00:03:44.986 A:middle
So as a user you might
find an interesting picture

74
00:03:45.086 --> 00:03:47.066 A:middle
and then you want to
go show it to somebody,

75
00:03:47.546 --> 00:03:50.556 A:middle
or the phone rings,
or something happens.

76
00:03:50.756 --> 00:03:53.186 A:middle
The application goes
into the background.

77
00:03:53.696 --> 00:03:58.316 A:middle
And the application can exit
if left alone for awhile

78
00:03:58.316 --> 00:04:01.216 A:middle
for various reasons, so I'm
going to force that here.

79
00:04:02.116 --> 00:04:04.056 A:middle
Now, I just want to
point out one thing.

80
00:04:05.066 --> 00:04:08.906 A:middle
Ordinarily when a user goes into
the switcher and flips an app

81
00:04:08.906 --> 00:04:11.356 A:middle
up like I just did,
it'll get rid

82
00:04:11.356 --> 00:04:13.296 A:middle
of all the state
restoration information.

83
00:04:14.076 --> 00:04:16.976 A:middle
We do that on purpose
to kind of save a user

84
00:04:16.976 --> 00:04:18.486 A:middle
if every time they run the app,

85
00:04:18.486 --> 00:04:21.146 A:middle
it starts up in a bad
state and they're stuck.

86
00:04:21.736 --> 00:04:23.796 A:middle
First thing a frustrated
user might do is go

87
00:04:23.796 --> 00:04:25.166 A:middle
in and flick that up.

88
00:04:25.496 --> 00:04:26.416 A:middle
We'll get rid of the state,

89
00:04:26.416 --> 00:04:28.296 A:middle
give them a clean
start if that happens.

90
00:04:28.416 --> 00:04:31.036 A:middle
Hopefully it won't,
but it's an out.

91
00:04:31.806 --> 00:04:35.776 A:middle
But for developers, sometimes
you don't want that to happen.

92
00:04:35.776 --> 00:04:37.706 A:middle
If you're trying to chase
a bug, you're trying

93
00:04:37.706 --> 00:04:40.026 A:middle
to diagnose something
or just simply testing,

94
00:04:40.026 --> 00:04:43.046 A:middle
it's very convenient to go in,
kill the app and restart it.

95
00:04:43.406 --> 00:04:44.596 A:middle
You don't want to lose the info.

96
00:04:44.906 --> 00:04:47.416 A:middle
And I'll talk about that a
little more later, but I'm using

97
00:04:47.416 --> 00:04:50.426 A:middle
that trick here just to make
the demo a little easier.

98
00:04:51.086 --> 00:04:54.276 A:middle
So the app's not running
now, and if the user walked

99
00:04:54.276 --> 00:04:55.466 A:middle
up to their friend
and said, "Hey,

100
00:04:55.466 --> 00:04:58.386 A:middle
look at this cool picture,"
well, let's see what happens

101
00:04:58.386 --> 00:04:59.776 A:middle
if we start it back up.

102
00:05:00.916 --> 00:05:02.736 A:middle
And it goes right
back to where it was.

103
00:05:03.926 --> 00:05:06.856 A:middle
It remembered that we weren't
showing any of the bars,

104
00:05:06.956 --> 00:05:10.176 A:middle
remembered the size of the
image, and even some things

105
00:05:10.176 --> 00:05:11.306 A:middle
that are behind the scenes.

106
00:05:11.346 --> 00:05:14.106 A:middle
Let's go here, I'm just
going to peel it back

107
00:05:14.106 --> 00:05:16.946 A:middle
with our cool new
gesture, and you can see

108
00:05:16.946 --> 00:05:18.726 A:middle
that it remembered
the scrollPosition

109
00:05:19.606 --> 00:05:20.786 A:middle
and the selected cell.

110
00:05:20.786 --> 00:05:24.156 A:middle
So that's a pretty
unexciting demo,

111
00:05:24.196 --> 00:05:25.756 A:middle
but it was supposed
to be actually.

112
00:05:26.166 --> 00:05:30.656 A:middle
The idea is it's predictable,
the users get what they want,

113
00:05:30.886 --> 00:05:32.606 A:middle
and it's nice and
easy for everybody.

114
00:05:33.246 --> 00:05:37.146 A:middle
So let's look at what we did
in order to accomplish that.

115
00:05:38.176 --> 00:05:41.536 A:middle
So first, what was
actually restored?

116
00:05:41.776 --> 00:05:44.876 A:middle
We saw it from the user's
perspective, but as a developer,

117
00:05:44.876 --> 00:05:46.776 A:middle
what were the constituent
pieces?

118
00:05:47.296 --> 00:05:50.306 A:middle
We had a navigation controller.

119
00:05:50.606 --> 00:05:54.266 A:middle
It remembered what
was pushed on it.

120
00:05:54.536 --> 00:05:56.876 A:middle
We also remembered
the scrollPosition

121
00:05:56.936 --> 00:06:00.156 A:middle
in our collection view
and the selected cell.

122
00:06:00.796 --> 00:06:05.006 A:middle
And finally, we remembered
what image we were showing,

123
00:06:06.206 --> 00:06:09.726 A:middle
the transformation we
applied to resize it.

124
00:06:10.926 --> 00:06:15.456 A:middle
So you'll find that when you
write state restoration code,

125
00:06:15.616 --> 00:06:19.446 A:middle
a lot of what you do is map what
your application has already

126
00:06:19.446 --> 00:06:22.326 A:middle
done into what you need
to save and restore.

127
00:06:23.186 --> 00:06:25.376 A:middle
Typically, you'll find
that there's a lot

128
00:06:25.376 --> 00:06:26.746 A:middle
of really strong parallels

129
00:06:26.746 --> 00:06:29.236 A:middle
between code you've
already written, ad in fact,

130
00:06:29.616 --> 00:06:31.566 A:middle
you'll be able to
leverage and reuse most

131
00:06:31.566 --> 00:06:32.486 A:middle
of the code you've written.

132
00:06:33.126 --> 00:06:36.786 A:middle
So here, let's see what happens
before we even saved state

133
00:06:37.086 --> 00:06:39.836 A:middle
when the user selected
that cell and we pushed

134
00:06:39.836 --> 00:06:41.186 A:middle
on that image view controller.

135
00:06:41.776 --> 00:06:44.526 A:middle
If we didn't take any action

136
00:06:44.526 --> 00:06:46.286 A:middle
and we just loaded
the view controller,

137
00:06:46.716 --> 00:06:48.306 A:middle
we wouldn't have an
image or a title.

138
00:06:49.456 --> 00:06:53.126 A:middle
We want to put something there,
and we also want to remember

139
00:06:53.126 --> 00:06:55.276 A:middle
that we're going to change
that title up top, too.

140
00:06:56.546 --> 00:06:57.346 A:middle
So what do we do?

141
00:06:58.426 --> 00:07:02.096 A:middle
Well, we have a method called
prepare for segway that you use

142
00:07:02.096 --> 00:07:03.336 A:middle
when you have storyboards.

143
00:07:03.956 --> 00:07:05.746 A:middle
So that's what I have
in the example here.

144
00:07:06.486 --> 00:07:08.026 A:middle
And then prepare for segway,

145
00:07:08.556 --> 00:07:10.706 A:middle
I hand the view controller
that's coming in,

146
00:07:10.706 --> 00:07:13.686 A:middle
our image view controller,
enough information

147
00:07:13.686 --> 00:07:16.296 A:middle
so that it can get the
image and set that title.

148
00:07:16.836 --> 00:07:20.056 A:middle
So now when I did that
segway, we actually have

149
00:07:20.056 --> 00:07:22.886 A:middle
that information right there.

150
00:07:23.486 --> 00:07:26.966 A:middle
So similarly, when I save and
restoreState, I'm going to want

151
00:07:26.966 --> 00:07:28.366 A:middle
to be able to maintain that.

152
00:07:29.026 --> 00:07:31.106 A:middle
So what do we do?

153
00:07:31.406 --> 00:07:33.286 A:middle
Well, let's look at
how we saved state.

154
00:07:33.956 --> 00:07:36.266 A:middle
When the application
goes in the background,

155
00:07:36.666 --> 00:07:39.686 A:middle
we're going to go all the view
controllers with identifiers,

156
00:07:39.736 --> 00:07:42.276 A:middle
all the view controllers that
need to save their state,

157
00:07:42.466 --> 00:07:43.616 A:middle
and give them a chance.

158
00:07:44.186 --> 00:07:48.546 A:middle
So we're going to call them
method encodeRestorableState

159
00:07:48.546 --> 00:07:49.116 A:middle
with coder.

160
00:07:49.116 --> 00:07:51.266 A:middle
We're going to hand
a key to archiver

161
00:07:51.266 --> 00:07:53.246 A:middle
where it can stash any
information it wants

162
00:07:53.246 --> 00:07:54.116 A:middle
to restore later.

163
00:07:54.566 --> 00:07:56.406 A:middle
So what do we need to save here?

164
00:07:58.236 --> 00:08:01.876 A:middle
Well, we've got the
image, also that title.

165
00:08:01.956 --> 00:08:05.566 A:middle
But we don't want to write
out the bits of the image

166
00:08:05.566 --> 00:08:08.336 A:middle
and actually save
an extra image file.

167
00:08:08.376 --> 00:08:12.176 A:middle
And in fact, if you think about
it, you probably have one place

168
00:08:12.176 --> 00:08:15.646 A:middle
that informs you of both the
image itself and that title.

169
00:08:16.406 --> 00:08:21.486 A:middle
So let's just save an identifier
that we can use later to look

170
00:08:21.486 --> 00:08:22.726 A:middle
up this information again.

171
00:08:23.246 --> 00:08:27.026 A:middle
And that as simple as
just encoding something

172
00:08:27.156 --> 00:08:29.686 A:middle
into that archiver that's
passed into the method.

173
00:08:29.686 --> 00:08:33.686 A:middle
And you can see here my image ID
is a string, so I'm just going

174
00:08:33.686 --> 00:08:35.926 A:middle
to encode an object,
give it a key

175
00:08:35.926 --> 00:08:37.366 A:middle
so I can look it back up later.

176
00:08:38.496 --> 00:08:39.296 A:middle
Anything else?

177
00:08:40.376 --> 00:08:41.956 A:middle
Well, we also remember whether

178
00:08:41.956 --> 00:08:45.196 A:middle
or not the user was showing the
bars on the top and the bottom.

179
00:08:45.576 --> 00:08:47.116 A:middle
So how do we save that?

180
00:08:47.996 --> 00:08:48.836 A:middle
Just as simple.

181
00:08:49.136 --> 00:08:50.676 A:middle
Just going to encode
a Boolean here,

182
00:08:51.656 --> 00:08:53.046 A:middle
and that's all we have to do.

183
00:08:54.696 --> 00:08:57.476 A:middle
So you'll notice, I'm not
showing a lot of code right now,

184
00:08:57.586 --> 00:08:59.786 A:middle
and there's a couple
reasons for that.

185
00:09:00.036 --> 00:09:03.966 A:middle
One is, what's important is to
try to get the concepts across,

186
00:09:03.966 --> 00:09:06.746 A:middle
so you can see what it is that
we're actually trying to do.

187
00:09:07.266 --> 00:09:10.026 A:middle
If I show you the code, it's
easy to kind of get lost

188
00:09:10.026 --> 00:09:12.406 A:middle
in the forest just
looking at it.

189
00:09:12.716 --> 00:09:15.416 A:middle
Now, we have released the code,
so you'll be able to check

190
00:09:15.416 --> 00:09:17.796 A:middle
out this whole example and
see everything I'm talking

191
00:09:17.796 --> 00:09:22.126 A:middle
about here in more detail, but
you can do it on your own time.

192
00:09:22.906 --> 00:09:27.276 A:middle
So how did we know to
call encodeRestorableState

193
00:09:27.276 --> 00:09:29.096 A:middle
for that view controller object?

194
00:09:29.976 --> 00:09:31.436 A:middle
Well, here's all
the view controllers

195
00:09:31.436 --> 00:09:33.206 A:middle
in my application so far.

196
00:09:33.386 --> 00:09:36.206 A:middle
We've got the navigation
controller, that collection view

197
00:09:36.206 --> 00:09:38.216 A:middle
with all the little
images, the thumbnails.

198
00:09:38.216 --> 00:09:41.156 A:middle
What we just looked at was
the image view controller,

199
00:09:41.266 --> 00:09:43.546 A:middle
and of course there's some
views that go along with those.

200
00:09:44.976 --> 00:09:47.416 A:middle
What you do is you give them
restoration identifiers.

201
00:09:47.696 --> 00:09:52.156 A:middle
That tells us that you want us
to keep track of those objects

202
00:09:52.576 --> 00:09:54.826 A:middle
when we save state and
when we restore it.

203
00:09:55.306 --> 00:09:58.736 A:middle
And we will also call the
encodeRestorableState method

204
00:09:58.886 --> 00:10:01.876 A:middle
on all of them so that
we save everything.

205
00:10:02.436 --> 00:10:07.256 A:middle
Okay. So how about
when we restoreState?

206
00:10:08.246 --> 00:10:11.486 A:middle
So at this point, the
application is starting back up.

207
00:10:12.746 --> 00:10:14.806 A:middle
Do you need to do
anything different

208
00:10:14.996 --> 00:10:18.386 A:middle
when an application starts up
when you're restoring state

209
00:10:18.386 --> 00:10:20.976 A:middle
versus the very first time
the application launches?

210
00:10:22.236 --> 00:10:25.056 A:middle
Well, when an application
launches, we tell the delegate

211
00:10:25.806 --> 00:10:30.386 A:middle
that we're starting up, and here
we just simply call or recall,

212
00:10:30.796 --> 00:10:34.396 A:middle
the method application Will
finishLaunching with options.

213
00:10:34.896 --> 00:10:37.006 A:middle
And you don't have to do
anything different here

214
00:10:37.376 --> 00:10:40.966 A:middle
in the state restoration
case; just proceed as normal.

215
00:10:41.626 --> 00:10:46.126 A:middle
Set up your base interface, will
either load your base interface

216
00:10:46.126 --> 00:10:47.756 A:middle
from a storyboard or a nib,

217
00:10:47.996 --> 00:10:50.056 A:middle
or you can execute
whatever code you have,

218
00:10:50.056 --> 00:10:53.686 A:middle
get your window visible,
and you're good to go,

219
00:10:53.686 --> 00:10:55.126 A:middle
and that's our starting point.

220
00:10:55.686 --> 00:10:58.436 A:middle
Then we're going to
go and we're going

221
00:10:58.436 --> 00:11:01.626 A:middle
to call the restorationMethods
for the objects

222
00:11:01.626 --> 00:11:02.576 A:middle
that are participating.

223
00:11:02.896 --> 00:11:05.366 A:middle
So in this case, let's look
at the image controller.

224
00:11:06.866 --> 00:11:10.116 A:middle
So here, you can see we're
starting off without our image.

225
00:11:10.246 --> 00:11:11.986 A:middle
How do we get it back?

226
00:11:12.716 --> 00:11:16.696 A:middle
We have a complimentary method,
decodeRestorableStateWithCoder.

227
00:11:17.106 --> 00:11:19.416 A:middle
It's kind of the analog to
the one I just showed you,

228
00:11:19.446 --> 00:11:22.166 A:middle
where you saved your
state, fairly logical.

229
00:11:22.166 --> 00:11:25.726 A:middle
So what we're going to
do is we're going to pull

230
00:11:25.726 --> 00:11:28.946 A:middle
in that image identifier,
which informs us both

231
00:11:28.946 --> 00:11:30.596 A:middle
of the image and the title.

