00:13:06.686 --> 00:13:08.626 A:middle
Well, it turns out you
didn't have to do anything.

267
00:13:08.946 --> 00:13:10.566 A:middle
You get all of that for free.

268
00:13:11.436 --> 00:13:12.556 A:middle
And how does that happen?

269
00:13:13.496 --> 00:13:16.186 A:middle
Well, I mentioned
before that when you set

270
00:13:16.186 --> 00:13:20.436 A:middle
up all the restoration
identifiers, it both informs us

271
00:13:20.436 --> 00:13:23.796 A:middle
of what needs to be saved but
also allows us to call methods

272
00:13:23.796 --> 00:13:25.076 A:middle
to save and restore state.

273
00:13:25.656 --> 00:13:28.856 A:middle
And we have a whole bunch
of base implementations

274
00:13:29.786 --> 00:13:32.416 A:middle
that save all the stuff for
you which is very convenient,

275
00:13:32.696 --> 00:13:34.316 A:middle
saving you the tedium of having

276
00:13:34.316 --> 00:13:36.176 A:middle
to write these very
common things.

277
00:13:36.246 --> 00:13:38.886 A:middle
So we keep track of a
lot of default behaviors,

278
00:13:39.246 --> 00:13:41.566 A:middle
a lot of information
automatically for you.

279
00:13:41.956 --> 00:13:44.606 A:middle
So you get a lot of leverage,
you get a lot of bang

280
00:13:44.606 --> 00:13:47.466 A:middle
for your buck for
setting this up.

281
00:13:50.656 --> 00:13:53.766 A:middle
So let's talk about
what's new in iOS 7.

282
00:13:55.196 --> 00:13:57.106 A:middle
We had some great
successes this year.

283
00:13:57.496 --> 00:13:59.066 A:middle
We've seen people
implementing this

284
00:13:59.066 --> 00:14:01.856 A:middle
and some really nice apps
incorporating state restoration.

285
00:14:02.576 --> 00:14:06.816 A:middle
And we felt that we had a nice
starting point for all this,

286
00:14:07.296 --> 00:14:08.866 A:middle
but that there were
some additional things

287
00:14:08.866 --> 00:14:12.096 A:middle
that we could do that would
make it even easier to use,

288
00:14:12.506 --> 00:14:16.076 A:middle
and also we wanted to continue
to grow as we add new facilities

289
00:14:16.256 --> 00:14:19.776 A:middle
to iOS and as apps continue
to get more sophisticated.

290
00:14:20.656 --> 00:14:24.696 A:middle
So let's look at what we've got.

291
00:14:25.276 --> 00:14:29.046 A:middle
We found that with view
controllers and views,

292
00:14:29.406 --> 00:14:33.116 A:middle
you sometimes wanted to also
have objects participate

293
00:14:33.116 --> 00:14:35.226 A:middle
in state restoration
like a data source

294
00:14:35.526 --> 00:14:37.966 A:middle
or some other nonview
controller object

295
00:14:38.616 --> 00:14:40.336 A:middle
in the same way the
view controllers

296
00:14:40.336 --> 00:14:41.526 A:middle
and views participate.

297
00:14:42.046 --> 00:14:46.906 A:middle
So we added the ability for any
object to be able to get added

298
00:14:46.906 --> 00:14:51.626 A:middle
to the state restoration graph
and save and restore its state.

299
00:14:52.326 --> 00:14:56.196 A:middle
Also, we've made it
easier for you to figure

300
00:14:56.196 --> 00:14:58.026 A:middle
out when you can apply state.

301
00:14:58.616 --> 00:15:01.266 A:middle
Something that's a
little tricky sometimes is

302
00:15:01.266 --> 00:15:05.096 A:middle
when your application restores
all of its state but isn't sure

303
00:15:05.096 --> 00:15:08.216 A:middle
of the order that different
things will get resorted in.

304
00:15:08.336 --> 00:15:11.056 A:middle
So after you've pulled the
view controller state back,

305
00:15:11.466 --> 00:15:13.926 A:middle
is it safe to go
and draw everything

306
00:15:13.926 --> 00:15:15.916 A:middle
on the screen, or
apply everything?

307
00:15:16.226 --> 00:15:18.366 A:middle
Well, it might depend
on other objects

308
00:15:18.366 --> 00:15:20.766 A:middle
that are also participating,
and we don't want you

309
00:15:20.766 --> 00:15:21.976 A:middle
to have to worry about that.

310
00:15:22.296 --> 00:15:24.926 A:middle
So I'll show how we've
made that easier to handle.

311
00:15:25.466 --> 00:15:29.836 A:middle
We've done a lot of work
with Snapshot handling.

312
00:15:30.916 --> 00:15:33.676 A:middle
Previously when an
application restored state,

313
00:15:33.676 --> 00:15:35.146 A:middle
we would show the default PNG,

314
00:15:35.146 --> 00:15:38.266 A:middle
and when the application
started up, we would just jump

315
00:15:38.636 --> 00:15:39.766 A:middle
to wherever its state was.

316
00:15:40.216 --> 00:15:42.486 A:middle
Now to provide a more
seamless experience,

317
00:15:42.746 --> 00:15:44.966 A:middle
we'll use a Snapshot
very aggressively,

318
00:15:45.146 --> 00:15:46.606 A:middle
and I'll go through
how you do that

319
00:15:46.606 --> 00:15:49.186 A:middle
and how you still have
some control over that.

320
00:15:50.056 --> 00:15:52.936 A:middle
There's also some small
enhancements I'll discuss.

321
00:15:53.766 --> 00:15:55.366 A:middle
We just keep adding new things.

322
00:15:55.696 --> 00:15:58.686 A:middle
Last year in 2012 when
I talked about this,

323
00:15:58.686 --> 00:16:02.126 A:middle
I mentioned you can implement
some state restoration

324
00:16:02.126 --> 00:16:04.716 A:middle
for your app and then
enhance it or extend it

325
00:16:04.716 --> 00:16:05.946 A:middle
as you add new features.

326
00:16:06.276 --> 00:16:09.286 A:middle
And we're taking our own advice
and doing the same thing,

327
00:16:09.556 --> 00:16:13.376 A:middle
so we started with the most
critical things, the basics,

328
00:16:13.566 --> 00:16:16.376 A:middle
and then we started to add
more things for this year.

329
00:16:18.106 --> 00:16:19.496 A:middle
So that's what's new.

330
00:16:20.326 --> 00:16:22.436 A:middle
Okay, first is generalized
objects.

331
00:16:23.076 --> 00:16:26.616 A:middle
So the idea here is to be
able to take objects that are

332
00:16:26.616 --> 00:16:29.696 A:middle
in view controllers and
views and also use them

333
00:16:29.696 --> 00:16:32.316 A:middle
in the same way in state
restoration as you've been able

334
00:16:32.316 --> 00:16:34.586 A:middle
to with our existing API.

335
00:16:35.696 --> 00:16:38.436 A:middle
So here's two of our
view controllers.

336
00:16:38.526 --> 00:16:41.876 A:middle
We have both the collection
view and then we also have

337
00:16:41.876 --> 00:16:42.696 A:middle
that image controller.

338
00:16:42.996 --> 00:16:46.216 A:middle
And a very common thing
in an application is

339
00:16:46.216 --> 00:16:48.686 A:middle
to have a data source object.

340
00:16:49.676 --> 00:16:52.846 A:middle
And with that data source,
you'll be referring to it

341
00:16:53.116 --> 00:16:54.846 A:middle
for multiple objects
in the system.

342
00:16:55.526 --> 00:16:58.186 A:middle
So here I'm using the
data source to inform you

343
00:16:58.186 --> 00:17:01.466 A:middle
of what images I have, how
many, what their titles are,

344
00:17:01.646 --> 00:17:03.606 A:middle
and to get the image
bits themselves --

345
00:17:03.606 --> 00:17:06.366 A:middle
kind of wraps over where
all those images are hiding

346
00:17:06.366 --> 00:17:07.856 A:middle
in the file system
so I don't have

347
00:17:07.925 --> 00:17:09.826 A:middle
to replicate that
code everywhere.

348
00:17:10.376 --> 00:17:13.626 A:middle
So I'm going to want
to be able to save

349
00:17:13.626 --> 00:17:15.935 A:middle
and restore a reference
to that directly.

350
00:17:16.006 --> 00:17:18.896 A:middle
I don't want to actually
encode the object completely

351
00:17:18.896 --> 00:17:22.316 A:middle
and make copies of it; I
just want to refer to it.

352
00:17:22.316 --> 00:17:24.396 A:middle
And the data source doesn't
actually need to save

353
00:17:24.396 --> 00:17:27.685 A:middle
and restore any state of its
own, but I will want to be able

354
00:17:27.685 --> 00:17:30.476 A:middle
to refer to it when I'm saving
state for other objects.

355
00:17:30.866 --> 00:17:34.006 A:middle
And something that's
kind of similar is

356
00:17:34.006 --> 00:17:36.306 A:middle
when you have a shared
object amongst the many view

357
00:17:36.306 --> 00:17:38.016 A:middle
controllers that
might be dynamic.

358
00:17:38.726 --> 00:17:41.856 A:middle
So I'm going to extend the
demo that I showed you before,

359
00:17:41.926 --> 00:17:43.976 A:middle
and we're going add an
Inspector so we can set

360
00:17:43.976 --> 00:17:46.626 A:middle
up some effects,
some image effects.

361
00:17:47.416 --> 00:17:50.426 A:middle
And here you can see that
that Inspector and the image

362
00:17:50.426 --> 00:17:52.026 A:middle
which is now kind of
a different color,

363
00:17:52.026 --> 00:17:54.016 A:middle
are sharing a filter object.

364
00:17:54.676 --> 00:17:57.446 A:middle
And this Filter object does
have some state, so it will want

365
00:17:57.446 --> 00:18:00.806 A:middle
to save and restore state,
and I'll also want to be able

366
00:18:00.806 --> 00:18:02.286 A:middle
to maintain those references.

367
00:18:02.846 --> 00:18:07.856 A:middle
So let's look at how our
example application has changed.

368
00:18:09.356 --> 00:18:13.426 A:middle
So I've got a data source object
here which I just described,

369
00:18:13.516 --> 00:18:17.896 A:middle
and it's being referred to by
both of the view controllers.

370
00:18:18.446 --> 00:18:22.016 A:middle
Now, I'm going to
extend the application

371
00:18:22.016 --> 00:18:24.786 A:middle
and add an Inspector, so I'm
going to present something

372
00:18:25.266 --> 00:18:27.546 A:middle
and it's going to
use a filter object.

373
00:18:28.196 --> 00:18:30.706 A:middle
In fact, I might have more
than one filter object,

374
00:18:31.836 --> 00:18:34.406 A:middle
and they'll be referred
to for multiple places.

375
00:18:35.216 --> 00:18:39.056 A:middle
So what I want to focus
on here is the data source

376
00:18:39.056 --> 00:18:39.976 A:middle
and these filters.

377
00:18:40.026 --> 00:18:41.466 A:middle
These are these objects
I'm referring

378
00:18:41.466 --> 00:18:44.056 A:middle
to as generalized
objects, and we're going

379
00:18:44.056 --> 00:18:46.516 A:middle
to see how they can play
along with everything else.

380
00:18:48.096 --> 00:18:52.426 A:middle
The first thing you need to do
if you want to use these objects

381
00:18:52.426 --> 00:18:54.326 A:middle
in state restoration
is register them.

382
00:18:54.976 --> 00:18:57.876 A:middle
We've added a new
method, on UI application.

383
00:18:58.476 --> 00:19:02.926 A:middle
It's called RegisterObject
for state restoration.

384
00:19:04.686 --> 00:19:06.936 A:middle
I'm glad we have code
Complete, because that's long.

385
00:19:08.356 --> 00:19:10.696 A:middle
This is very similar to setting

386
00:19:10.696 --> 00:19:13.096 A:middle
up a restoration identifier
on a view controller.

387
00:19:14.116 --> 00:19:16.416 A:middle
You pass in the object
and you can see

388
00:19:16.416 --> 00:19:19.106 A:middle
that it actually implements
a new protocol, and we'll get

389
00:19:19.106 --> 00:19:22.606 A:middle
to that in a minute,
then you also pass us a

390
00:19:22.606 --> 00:19:24.196 A:middle
stringRestoration identifier.

391
00:19:24.916 --> 00:19:28.096 A:middle
Now, for view controllers and
views we made this a property,

392
00:19:28.826 --> 00:19:31.926 A:middle
but I didn't want to
force developers to have

393
00:19:32.026 --> 00:19:35.656 A:middle
to subclass a base class
that we would contrive just

394
00:19:35.656 --> 00:19:37.216 A:middle
so that they could
register an object.

395
00:19:38.136 --> 00:19:39.736 A:middle
We need to hook in,
we need to know

396
00:19:39.736 --> 00:19:41.016 A:middle
when the object's registered.

397
00:19:41.276 --> 00:19:43.646 A:middle
I didn't want you to have to
subclass something and make sure

398
00:19:43.646 --> 00:19:46.796 A:middle
to call Super, so we felt
this was a nice clear way

399
00:19:47.076 --> 00:19:48.996 A:middle
to identify what's
participating.

400
00:19:49.086 --> 00:19:51.046 A:middle
You just call this
method with your object

401
00:19:51.046 --> 00:19:53.546 A:middle
and the identifier you
want, you're good to go.

402
00:19:54.466 --> 00:19:57.856 A:middle
So let's look at that
protocol that I mentioned.

403
00:19:57.856 --> 00:19:59.756 A:middle
It's called UI state restoring.

404
00:20:00.376 --> 00:20:05.226 A:middle
It has the methods to save and
restore state for that object.

405
00:20:05.866 --> 00:20:07.356 A:middle
These are actually optional.

406
00:20:07.356 --> 00:20:09.716 A:middle
There's some cases where you
won't actually need to save

407
00:20:09.716 --> 00:20:12.176 A:middle
and restore anything; you
just want to add the object

408
00:20:12.586 --> 00:20:19.026 A:middle
to the graph of objects
we're keeping track of.

409
00:20:19.476 --> 00:20:21.976 A:middle
We also have a property
that you can use

410
00:20:22.246 --> 00:20:24.286 A:middle
to scope the object's
identifier.

411
00:20:25.166 --> 00:20:27.876 A:middle
Sometimes you might want
to use the same object

412
00:20:27.876 --> 00:20:30.696 A:middle
or the same class of object
in more than one place,

413
00:20:30.876 --> 00:20:33.896 A:middle
and you'll have creation
code or something that sets

414
00:20:33.896 --> 00:20:37.846 A:middle
up the identifier, and it would
be contrived to have to give it,

415
00:20:37.846 --> 00:20:39.946 A:middle
the restoration identifier
some weird name just

416
00:20:39.976 --> 00:20:40.996 A:middle
because of where you put it.

417
00:20:41.326 --> 00:20:44.286 A:middle
As an example, let's
say on an iPad,

418
00:20:44.286 --> 00:20:45.606 A:middle
you have an image editing app

419
00:20:45.756 --> 00:20:47.616 A:middle
where you can apply
two different effects.

420
00:20:47.616 --> 00:20:52.116 A:middle
So on the left here, you
can have one set of effects

421
00:20:52.256 --> 00:20:53.326 A:middle
that you're showing
on the image,

422
00:20:53.506 --> 00:20:55.676 A:middle
and you might have a
different set on the right side

423
00:20:55.676 --> 00:20:58.586 A:middle
so the user can kind of
compare and contrast approaches.

424
00:20:59.316 --> 00:21:01.906 A:middle
And you might be using
the same effect objects,

425
00:21:01.906 --> 00:21:04.446 A:middle
or the same filter
objects, and you just want

426
00:21:04.446 --> 00:21:05.606 A:middle
to give them the same name.

427
00:21:06.026 --> 00:21:08.376 A:middle
You can scope them by
setting their parent.

428
00:21:08.906 --> 00:21:11.006 A:middle
Often you'll set that
to a view controller.

429
00:21:11.476 --> 00:21:13.706 A:middle
You might set it to
another restorable object.

430
00:21:14.836 --> 00:21:16.616 A:middle
This is what we implicitly do

431
00:21:16.766 --> 00:21:18.336 A:middle
for the view controller
hierarchy.

432
00:21:18.586 --> 00:21:21.416 A:middle
We actually keep track of
the parent of an object based

433
00:21:21.416 --> 00:21:24.056 A:middle
on whether it was
presented, or if it's pushed

434
00:21:24.056 --> 00:21:26.896 A:middle
on a navigation stack or in
another collection controller

435
00:21:26.896 --> 00:21:30.236 A:middle
like a tab view, and here
we make it very explicit

436
00:21:30.236 --> 00:21:32.156 A:middle
for you to do.

437
00:21:32.776 --> 00:21:37.326 A:middle
Also, in some cases, the objects
may or may not exist depending

438
00:21:37.326 --> 00:21:38.806 A:middle
on what the user has done.

439
00:21:38.886 --> 00:21:41.146 A:middle
So I showed you this
beginning of the demo

440
00:21:41.146 --> 00:21:43.646 A:middle
and I didn't create any
filters, so there aren't any

441
00:21:43.646 --> 00:21:44.936 A:middle
in my examples so far.

442
00:21:45.926 --> 00:21:48.556 A:middle
Now, if my application
starts back up, I don't want

443
00:21:48.556 --> 00:21:51.046 A:middle
to create every possible
object I might have

444
00:21:51.086 --> 00:21:53.026 A:middle
on the off chance I
might be restoring them.

445
00:21:53.026 --> 00:21:56.656 A:middle
It'd be a lot nicer if somebody
kept track of that for me

446
00:21:56.926 --> 00:22:00.276 A:middle
and told the application, "hey,
