00:23:22.306 --> 00:23:24.096 A:middle
at a little bit of
the information

477
00:23:24.096 --> 00:23:27.656 A:middle
that was saved to
help inform that.

478
00:23:27.656 --> 00:23:30.926 A:middle
Also, let's say that you
have a dynamic database,

479
00:23:30.926 --> 00:23:34.466 A:middle
and we're restoring an object
that no longer corresponds

480
00:23:34.466 --> 00:23:35.836 A:middle
to anything in the database.

481
00:23:35.836 --> 00:23:38.636 A:middle
You might have synchronized
the database or changed things

482
00:23:38.636 --> 00:23:40.496 A:middle
so that that object
doesn't exist.

483
00:23:41.046 --> 00:23:44.156 A:middle
You can look in the coder
to find out if indeed

484
00:23:44.156 --> 00:23:47.206 A:middle
that object is still around
or not, and if it isn't,

485
00:23:47.206 --> 00:23:49.046 A:middle
you can just return
nill from this method.

486
00:23:49.336 --> 00:23:52.236 A:middle
We'll be fine; we'll just
stop paying attention to it,

487
00:23:52.236 --> 00:23:55.186 A:middle
we won't try to restore
its state.

488
00:23:55.666 --> 00:23:58.126 A:middle
You return one of these
state restoring objects,

489
00:23:58.526 --> 00:24:01.036 A:middle
and you'll all done.

