00:33:00.406 --> 00:33:02.386 A:middle
to restore them only
in the cases

666
00:33:02.386 --> 00:33:05.156 A:middle
where the user was actually
using them, when they existed

667
00:33:05.156 --> 00:33:06.386 A:middle
at the time we saved state.

668
00:33:06.716 --> 00:33:08.066 A:middle
So that's what we'll do here.

669
00:33:08.976 --> 00:33:10.256 A:middle
So we'll recreate them,

670
00:33:11.196 --> 00:33:14.566 A:middle
we'll then restore
references, here's our filters.

671
00:33:15.006 --> 00:33:16.956 A:middle
So we've just created
them again.

672
00:33:18.216 --> 00:33:21.746 A:middle
The state restoration runtime
will ask the restoration class

673
00:33:21.746 --> 00:33:24.416 A:middle
to create them by calling
objectWithRestoration

674
00:33:24.416 --> 00:33:25.136 A:middle
identifier path.

675
00:33:25.586 --> 00:33:27.816 A:middle
Now, you'll notice they
don't have any state yet,

676
00:33:27.816 --> 00:33:29.306 A:middle
so what's going to happen next?

677
00:33:29.786 --> 00:33:32.526 A:middle
Well, we're going to restore
our references to them,

678
00:33:32.866 --> 00:33:34.406 A:middle
but they still don't
have any state.

679
00:33:34.406 --> 00:33:37.506 A:middle
We're just going to wire them
up to our view controllers,

680
00:33:37.636 --> 00:33:39.826 A:middle
so we can see there I
haven't actually applied

681
00:33:39.826 --> 00:33:40.656 A:middle
that filter yet.

682
00:33:42.016 --> 00:33:45.206 A:middle
So we'll let the filter
object restore its own state

683
00:33:45.206 --> 00:33:46.146 A:middle
recalling decode.

684
00:33:46.816 --> 00:33:48.256 A:middle
So now it's restored its state.

685
00:33:48.256 --> 00:33:50.146 A:middle
I don't want you
to have to worry

686
00:33:50.146 --> 00:33:52.566 A:middle
about what order this all
happens in, so I'm going to talk

687
00:33:52.566 --> 00:33:55.806 A:middle
about how we can leverage this
later and make it real simple

688
00:33:55.806 --> 00:33:58.496 A:middle
to apply it so that
you then eventually get

689
00:33:58.496 --> 00:34:00.676 A:middle
that nice sepia look
on your picture,

690
00:34:01.416 --> 00:34:05.316 A:middle
and we're back to where we were.

691
00:34:05.966 --> 00:34:07.756 A:middle
So let's talk about
how we apply the state.

692
00:34:08.085 --> 00:34:11.056 A:middle
The first thing we do as we're
restoring is get back our image.

693
00:34:11.056 --> 00:34:13.755 A:middle
But we can't go and
apply that filter yet.

694
00:34:13.926 --> 00:34:15.886 A:middle
The filter might not
even exist at this point.

695
00:34:15.886 --> 00:34:19.485 A:middle
We're just in the decode method
for this view controller object.

696
00:34:20.326 --> 00:34:22.626 A:middle
And at some point we are
going to go grab that filter.

697
00:34:22.626 --> 00:34:24.886 A:middle
It'll get created, it
will restore it state.

698
00:34:25.176 --> 00:34:26.366 A:middle
Now we're good to go.

699
00:34:26.505 --> 00:34:28.206 A:middle
Now we can apply that filter.

700
00:34:28.636 --> 00:34:30.456 A:middle
But when? How do we know?

701
00:34:31.576 --> 00:34:33.505 A:middle
So we've added a new method.

702
00:34:35.255 --> 00:34:37.966 A:middle
This method's for view
controllers as well as any

703
00:34:37.966 --> 00:34:39.565 A:middle
of the state restoring objects,

704
00:34:39.636 --> 00:34:42.946 A:middle
and it decouples decoding
your state from trying

705
00:34:42.946 --> 00:34:45.466 A:middle
to apply what might be
more of a global state

706
00:34:45.466 --> 00:34:46.726 A:middle
across the whole application.

707
00:34:46.726 --> 00:34:49.286 A:middle
It's just a simple
little method,

708
00:34:49.286 --> 00:34:51.716 A:middle
application finished
restoring state.

709
00:34:52.016 --> 00:34:53.626 A:middle
It's kind of like awakeFromNib.

710
00:34:53.916 --> 00:34:56.795 A:middle
It's telling you, everything
is restored at state;

711
00:34:56.795 --> 00:34:58.936 A:middle
everything is created
that we know about;

712
00:34:58.936 --> 00:35:00.246 A:middle
it's safe to go in the water.

713
00:35:00.556 --> 00:35:02.226 A:middle
Go on, apply your filter.

714
00:35:02.806 --> 00:35:07.936 A:middle
So if we didn't have this, you'd
probably have code like this.

715
00:35:07.936 --> 00:35:10.046 A:middle
Now, I mentioned I wasn't
going to show you much code;

716
00:35:10.046 --> 00:35:11.736 A:middle
this is actually the
only code slide --

717
00:35:12.176 --> 00:35:14.866 A:middle
so mainly because I
like this cool effect.

718
00:35:15.646 --> 00:35:18.716 A:middle
So the idea here is I don't
want to update the image

719
00:35:18.716 --> 00:35:20.026 A:middle
when I'm decoding my state

720
00:35:20.026 --> 00:35:23.126 A:middle
because everything else might
not exist yet, so I'm just going

721
00:35:23.126 --> 00:35:25.196 A:middle
to decode my state
and not do that thing.

722
00:35:25.746 --> 00:35:29.266 A:middle
And then when application
FinishedResotringState is

723
00:35:29.266 --> 00:35:31.326 A:middle
called, I'll call updateImage.

724
00:35:32.246 --> 00:35:34.706 A:middle
And if you're wondering,
what's this updateImage,

725
00:35:35.566 --> 00:35:37.356 A:middle
imagine I don't have
any stateRestoration.

726
00:35:38.076 --> 00:35:39.746 A:middle
I have a segway to
a view controller,

727
00:35:39.746 --> 00:35:41.526 A:middle
I tell it what image
I want it to show,

728
00:35:41.646 --> 00:35:43.766 A:middle
there might be some
filters that are set up.

729
00:35:43.766 --> 00:35:46.086 A:middle
So I'm going to write some
code that goes and fetches

730
00:35:46.086 --> 00:35:48.996 A:middle
that imageAppliestoFilter,
sets the title, do all of that.

731
00:35:49.346 --> 00:35:51.356 A:middle
That's updateImage,
and if you look

732
00:35:51.356 --> 00:35:54.276 A:middle
at the sample code you'll see
that I'm able to just reuse

733
00:35:54.276 --> 00:35:58.126 A:middle
that method when the application
restores its state here,

734
00:35:58.126 --> 00:36:01.376 A:middle
so I don't have to go and write
a whole big bifurcated strategy

735
00:36:01.846 --> 00:36:04.776 A:middle
for restoring the image and
setting it up in this case

736
00:36:04.776 --> 00:36:10.126 A:middle
versus that case; got one
cute little piece of code.

737
00:36:10.326 --> 00:36:13.656 A:middle
So there is one area where
we got a number of questions

738
00:36:13.656 --> 00:36:15.276 A:middle
and they were kind
of the same question.

739
00:36:16.356 --> 00:36:18.886 A:middle
When do I have to
create my objects,

740
00:36:19.136 --> 00:36:21.476 A:middle
and when will you
automatically find the ones I've

741
00:36:21.516 --> 00:36:22.476 A:middle
already created?

742
00:36:22.886 --> 00:36:24.386 A:middle
You have a lot of
view controllers.

743
00:36:24.596 --> 00:36:26.896 A:middle
You have some of these new
state resorting objects.

744
00:36:27.286 --> 00:36:30.966 A:middle
And some of them exist when
the application starts up;

745
00:36:31.336 --> 00:36:33.176 A:middle
others come into
being dynamically.

746
00:36:33.666 --> 00:36:35.626 A:middle
So let's look at that
in a little more detail.

747
00:36:36.216 --> 00:36:39.356 A:middle
So if you think of the set of
application objects you have,

748
00:36:40.006 --> 00:36:42.356 A:middle
I like to refer to
everything that exists

749
00:36:42.356 --> 00:36:45.546 A:middle
when the application is
already started as base objects.

750
00:36:45.966 --> 00:36:49.476 A:middle
These are loaded from a
storyboard or from various nibs.

751
00:36:50.076 --> 00:36:51.366 A:middle
They're created by your code

752
00:36:51.366 --> 00:36:53.766 A:middle
in application
WillFinishLaunchingwithOptions.

753
00:36:54.166 --> 00:36:55.926 A:middle
Before we do state restoration,

754
00:36:56.176 --> 00:36:58.416 A:middle
they're already in
play, they exist.

755
00:36:58.776 --> 00:37:02.116 A:middle
So if they're going to be using
state restoration and we need

756
00:37:02.116 --> 00:37:04.776 A:middle
to find them, you don't
have to do anything.

757
00:37:05.226 --> 00:37:07.256 A:middle
We'll just be able to
find them and look them

758
00:37:07.256 --> 00:37:09.326 A:middle
up because we've got some
magical little tables

759
00:37:09.326 --> 00:37:10.796 A:middle
where we keep track
of everything.

760
00:37:11.566 --> 00:37:14.396 A:middle
What about all the
dynamic objects?

761
00:37:14.556 --> 00:37:16.576 A:middle
These are presented controllers,

762
00:37:16.816 --> 00:37:19.626 A:middle
view controllers you might have
pushed on a navigation stack,

763
00:37:20.216 --> 00:37:21.706 A:middle
some of these restorable objects

764
00:37:21.706 --> 00:37:26.056 A:middle
like those filters --
how do you get them?

765
00:37:26.286 --> 00:37:29.066 A:middle
Well, if it's a view controller
and it's in a storyboard,

766
00:37:29.656 --> 00:37:31.826 A:middle
you actually can get
it completely for free.

767
00:37:32.086 --> 00:37:33.096 A:middle
We'll just find it.

768
00:37:33.336 --> 00:37:35.896 A:middle
That's because we know what
storyboard it came from,

769
00:37:35.896 --> 00:37:38.016 A:middle
we know what its
storyboard identifier was,

770
00:37:38.326 --> 00:37:39.516 A:middle
so we can keep track of it.

771
00:37:40.106 --> 00:37:42.326 A:middle
So you'll notice
when I presented some

772
00:37:42.326 --> 00:37:45.156 A:middle
of those view controllers there,
I didn't show any code to have

773
00:37:45.226 --> 00:37:48.206 A:middle
to recreate them and represent
them; we were able to go

774
00:37:48.206 --> 00:37:50.646 A:middle
and hoist them out of
storyboards ourselves.

775
00:37:51.536 --> 00:37:54.476 A:middle
However, if it's
not in a storyboard,

776
00:37:54.996 --> 00:37:56.906 A:middle
or if you want a
little bit more control,

777
00:37:56.906 --> 00:37:58.736 A:middle
you have to write a
little bit of code,

778
00:37:58.866 --> 00:38:00.946 A:middle
and that's where the
restoration class comes in.

779
00:38:02.276 --> 00:38:05.166 A:middle
So you can use a restoration
class for view controllers

780
00:38:05.166 --> 00:38:08.686 A:middle
in the same way I showed you for
these new generalized objects.

781
00:38:09.266 --> 00:38:12.696 A:middle
And also for view
controllers, as a fallback,

782
00:38:13.086 --> 00:38:14.786 A:middle
we'll ask the application
delegate

783
00:38:14.786 --> 00:38:16.806 A:middle
for them if all else fails.

784
00:38:17.426 --> 00:38:19.756 A:middle
Now, if you implement
a restoration class,

785
00:38:20.146 --> 00:38:21.686 A:middle
that trumps everything.

786
00:38:22.526 --> 00:38:23.766 A:middle
That gives you control.

787
00:38:24.136 --> 00:38:26.766 A:middle
Let's say -- going back
to my earlier example --

788
00:38:27.686 --> 00:38:30.316 A:middle
maybe you have a dynamic
database with images.

789
00:38:30.316 --> 00:38:33.386 A:middle
These can synchronize and
images come, images go.

790
00:38:33.796 --> 00:38:37.486 A:middle
So if the image that was being
shown when you saved state isn't

791
00:38:37.486 --> 00:38:40.276 A:middle
in the database when you
restore it, you may not want

792
00:38:40.276 --> 00:38:41.926 A:middle
to bring back that
view controller

793
00:38:41.926 --> 00:38:44.476 A:middle
and show us something
ugly like imageNotFound.

794
00:38:45.536 --> 00:38:47.116 A:middle
You want to just
avoid it altogether.

795
00:38:47.116 --> 00:38:49.796 A:middle
And it's always fine to
return nill when we ask

796
00:38:49.796 --> 00:38:50.726 A:middle
for a view controller.

797
00:38:50.726 --> 00:38:51.826 A:middle
We'll do the right thing.

798
00:38:51.906 --> 00:38:54.296 A:middle
If it was presented, we
just won't present it;

799
00:38:54.296 --> 00:38:56.716 A:middle
if it was pushed on
the navigation stack,

800
00:38:57.626 --> 00:39:00.106 A:middle
we'll go one back and
so on until we get

801
00:39:00.106 --> 00:39:02.136 A:middle
to a view controller
that still exists.

802
00:39:02.956 --> 00:39:05.896 A:middle
So we give you that control
to make sure that we don't go

803
00:39:06.046 --> 00:39:08.376 A:middle
and force you into
some boundary situation

804
00:39:08.376 --> 00:39:11.636 A:middle
where you don't have all the
assets you need that make sense.

805
00:39:14.436 --> 00:39:18.056 A:middle
So here's the base objects in
the example app I showed you:

806
00:39:18.546 --> 00:39:21.666 A:middle
the data source, that
navigation controller,

807
00:39:22.356 --> 00:39:23.266 A:middle
and the collection view.

808
00:39:23.546 --> 00:39:25.306 A:middle
They were all in
my main storyboard;

809
00:39:25.436 --> 00:39:27.106 A:middle
they just got created
by the time I got

810
00:39:27.106 --> 00:39:29.606 A:middle
into application
WillFinishLaunchingwithOptions.

811
00:39:29.916 --> 00:39:35.086 A:middle
And I put that Inspector in a
storyboard, so then I was able

812
00:39:35.086 --> 00:39:36.476 A:middle
to just completely
forget about it.

813
00:39:36.476 --> 00:39:37.956 A:middle
I didn't have to recreate it;

814
00:39:37.956 --> 00:39:40.396 A:middle
it just magically came
back, it was presented.

815
00:39:41.246 --> 00:39:43.456 A:middle
Now, if I want a
little more control,

816
00:39:43.956 --> 00:39:46.796 A:middle
I can take that image
controller, and even if it's

817
00:39:46.796 --> 00:39:49.576 A:middle
in a storyboard I can still
give it a restoration class,

818
00:39:49.806 --> 00:39:52.976 A:middle
or if I was creating it out
of whole cloth, myself encode,

819
00:39:53.126 --> 00:39:54.736 A:middle
I'd give it a restoration class.

820
00:39:55.166 --> 00:39:58.856 A:middle
And the filters, as we saw,
had a restoration class

821
00:39:59.106 --> 00:40:00.806 A:middle
which recreated them on demand.

822
00:40:01.066 --> 00:40:03.236 A:middle
So when you think
about your objects

823
00:40:03.236 --> 00:40:05.596 A:middle
and which ones need
a restoration class,

824
00:40:05.686 --> 00:40:07.496 A:middle
which ones you'll
have to recreate

825
00:40:07.496 --> 00:40:08.496 A:middle
when we're restoring state,

826
00:40:08.836 --> 00:40:11.426 A:middle
break them up in your
mind, what's a base object.

827
00:40:12.466 --> 00:40:13.636 A:middle
Then you don't have
to do anything,

828
00:40:14.026 --> 00:40:15.656 A:middle
and of the dynamic objects,

829
00:40:15.926 --> 00:40:18.086 A:middle
which ones do I actually
need control of

830
00:40:18.086 --> 00:40:19.666 A:middle
or what am I going
to have to create?

831
00:40:20.186 --> 00:40:21.156 A:middle
Makes it a lot simpler.

832
00:40:21.636 --> 00:40:27.216 A:middle
I mentioned we did a lot
with Snapshot handling.

833
00:40:27.866 --> 00:40:31.136 A:middle
So in iOS 6, we wouldn't
use the Snapshot at all.

834
00:40:31.136 --> 00:40:32.946 A:middle
And that was kind of jarring,

835
00:40:32.946 --> 00:40:35.706 A:middle
because the application would
come up with the default PNG,

836
00:40:36.066 --> 00:40:39.506 A:middle
restore its state and then kind
of slap you when it went back

837
00:40:39.506 --> 00:40:40.896 A:middle
to where it actually was.

838
00:40:41.056 --> 00:40:43.636 A:middle
So we're trying to be
much more aggressive now.

839
00:40:43.686 --> 00:40:47.106 A:middle
And we'll show the
Snapshot wherever we can.

840
00:40:48.106 --> 00:40:49.666 A:middle
So when we launch
an application,

841
00:40:49.926 --> 00:40:51.596 A:middle
if the Snapshot's available

842
00:40:51.596 --> 00:40:54.426 A:middle
and if we can use
it, we'll show that.

843
00:40:54.426 --> 00:40:56.356 A:middle
It looks much more seamless.

844
00:40:56.896 --> 00:40:59.806 A:middle
However, there might be cases
where you want to use it,

845
00:40:59.806 --> 00:41:01.426 A:middle
so we give you some control.

846
00:41:01.426 --> 00:41:02.656 A:middle
We've added a new API.

847
00:41:03.386 --> 00:41:06.246 A:middle
This is on UI application
and you can tell it

848
00:41:06.246 --> 00:41:09.166 A:middle
to ignore Snapshot
on the next launch.

849
00:41:09.736 --> 00:41:12.366 A:middle
You'll do this while
we're saving your state.

850
00:41:12.836 --> 00:41:15.846 A:middle
So if we're saving state in
one of your view controllers,

851
00:41:16.086 --> 00:41:19.316 A:middle
notices, this is kind of tricky.

852
00:41:19.796 --> 00:41:21.166 A:middle
I might not come back exactly

853
00:41:21.166 --> 00:41:24.126 A:middle
to the same place,
ignore the Snapshot.

854
00:41:24.746 --> 00:41:26.116 A:middle
Then we'll use the default PNG.

855
00:41:26.756 --> 00:41:29.796 A:middle
That means only one of two
things will ever happen.

856
00:41:30.576 --> 00:41:33.896 A:middle
We'll show the same Snapshot
that we're going to launch to,

857
00:41:34.216 --> 00:41:37.146 A:middle
or we'll show the default
PNG, which is predictable

858
00:41:37.146 --> 00:41:40.206 A:middle
and at least it's somewhat
familiar, second best choice.

859
00:41:40.826 --> 00:41:43.936 A:middle
So why would you want us to
ignore the Snapshot, though?

860
00:41:44.566 --> 00:41:45.716 A:middle
Well, here's some examples.

861
00:41:46.506 --> 00:41:49.206 A:middle
Maybe your application is
showing a network error.

862
00:41:50.076 --> 00:41:52.186 A:middle
Can't get on network;
please try again later.

863
00:41:52.186 --> 00:41:55.306 A:middle
Click the application in
the background, it exits,

864
00:41:55.556 --> 00:41:58.886 A:middle
user goes to maybe a better
coffee shop with free Wi-Fi,

865
00:41:59.576 --> 00:42:01.136 A:middle
they start the app up again.

866
00:42:01.136 --> 00:42:04.736 A:middle
And it would be kind of
silly for this network thing

867
00:42:04.736 --> 00:42:06.376 A:middle
to be showing, seeing

868
00:42:06.376 --> 00:42:08.916 A:middle
that there's an error
freaking the poor user out,

869
00:42:08.916 --> 00:42:11.046 A:middle
and then have it
just dismiss itself

870
00:42:11.046 --> 00:42:12.546 A:middle
or disappear when
the app started.

871
00:42:14.336 --> 00:42:17.616 A:middle
You also might have things
like a table view of data

872
00:42:17.616 --> 00:42:18.826 A:middle
that changes frequently.

873
00:42:19.566 --> 00:42:22.176 A:middle
Maybe you have the top
10 awesome kitten videos

874
00:42:22.176 --> 00:42:25.556 A:middle
of the day, something
like that, and they tend

875
00:42:25.556 --> 00:42:28.076 A:middle
to change pretty quickly, I
can tell you from experience.

876
00:42:28.396 --> 00:42:35.016 A:middle
So the application when it
starts up, you might not want

877
00:42:35.016 --> 00:42:37.956 A:middle
to show a list of things
that you're actually not --

878
00:42:37.956 --> 00:42:41.606 A:middle
eventually going to land on,
and the user's stabbing away

879
00:42:41.606 --> 00:42:44.216 A:middle
at this video and it doesn't
show up, so it might be better

880
00:42:44.566 --> 00:42:45.776 A:middle
to avoid that altogether.

881
00:42:47.406 --> 00:42:49.306 A:middle
There's also some implicit cases

882
00:42:49.306 --> 00:42:53.046 A:middle
where we'll actually detect
Snapshot wouldn't be the best

883
00:42:53.046 --> 00:42:55.356 A:middle
choice, so there's
a couple there.

884
00:42:55.616 --> 00:42:58.466 A:middle
One is, if the top most view
controller doesn't have a

885
00:42:58.466 --> 00:43:01.496 A:middle
restoration identifier,
we're going to assume, okay,

886
00:43:01.496 --> 00:43:02.636 A:middle
you're app's pretty awesome

887
00:43:02.636 --> 00:43:04.296 A:middle
and it restores state,
which is great.

888
00:43:04.456 --> 00:43:06.256 A:middle
Thank you, but we can
tell that you're not going

889
00:43:06.256 --> 00:43:07.206 A:middle
to restore to this one.

890
00:43:07.616 --> 00:43:09.846 A:middle
There might be some
boundary area of the app

891
00:43:09.896 --> 00:43:12.556 A:middle
that users rarely go
to, setting something

892
00:43:12.556 --> 00:43:14.276 A:middle
up that they would
typically only do once.

893
00:43:14.676 --> 00:43:17.566 A:middle
That might not be a battle worth
fighting for the first release,

894
00:43:17.606 --> 00:43:20.846 A:middle
so you may not save the state of
that particular view controller

895
00:43:20.846 --> 00:43:23.426 A:middle
and you may be focusing
on more important things,

896
00:43:23.906 --> 00:43:25.926 A:middle
such as articles they're
reading and things like that.

897
00:43:26.416 --> 00:43:29.536 A:middle
So in that case, if we
detect there's no restoration

898
00:43:29.536 --> 00:43:31.946 A:middle
identifier, we won't show
the Snapshot; we don't want

899
00:43:31.946 --> 00:43:34.936 A:middle
to give the user false hope
when it's starting back up.

900
00:43:35.886 --> 00:43:39.516 A:middle
Also, there may be some
things that we don't restore,

901
00:43:40.136 --> 00:43:41.776 A:middle
and I'll show you
an example of that.

902
00:43:42.216 --> 00:43:44.136 A:middle
So there's a whole
bunch of areas

903
00:43:44.136 --> 00:43:47.386 A:middle
where it's either inefficient
to try to restore everything

904
00:43:47.386 --> 00:43:49.086 A:middle
or it's just complicated enough

905
00:43:49.386 --> 00:43:50.696 A:middle
that we haven't gotten
to it yet.

906
00:43:50.696 --> 00:43:52.796 A:middle
Similar to the advice
I gave last year

907
00:43:52.796 --> 00:43:54.676 A:middle
where you take an
approach where you start

908
00:43:54.676 --> 00:43:57.226 A:middle
with the most important
things and then add to it,

909
00:43:57.686 --> 00:43:59.066 A:middle
we're in the same boat.

910
00:43:59.066 --> 00:44:01.006 A:middle
So we don't want
to show a Snapshot

911
00:44:01.006 --> 00:44:01.946 A:middle
if we know we're not going

912
00:44:01.946 --> 00:44:04.026 A:middle
to come exactly back
to the same place.

913
00:44:04.816 --> 00:44:08.596 A:middle
So I'm going to do another demo,
but this one's kind of quick,

914
00:44:08.696 --> 00:44:12.706 A:middle
so I'm actually going
to use a movie.

915
00:44:13.106 --> 00:44:15.796 A:middle
So here's our application,
we're looking at the image,

916
00:44:16.146 --> 00:44:18.406 A:middle
and let's say that I go
to the activity sheet.

917
00:44:19.676 --> 00:44:24.186 A:middle
Okay, so we actually don't share
the activity view controller

918
00:44:24.186 --> 00:44:27.126 A:middle
state, and there's a couple
of reasons why we don't.

919
00:44:27.876 --> 00:44:30.916 A:middle
Mostly, it's because the
application is handing us a

920
00:44:30.916 --> 00:44:31.946 A:middle
whole bunch of data.

921
00:44:31.946 --> 00:44:34.656 A:middle
It could have handed us a
video to mail to somebody

922
00:44:34.656 --> 00:44:38.666 A:middle
to really annoy them, it could
have handed us a lot of content,

923
00:44:39.166 --> 00:44:42.326 A:middle
and it can often be a
[inaudible] content or something

924
00:44:42.326 --> 00:44:45.376 A:middle
that may not exist when the
application starts back up.

925
00:44:45.616 --> 00:44:48.026 A:middle
So it would be both
be very costly for us

926
00:44:48.076 --> 00:44:52.906 A:middle
to save all this data
and it might also bite us

927
00:44:52.906 --> 00:44:55.026 A:middle
when we start the app back
up but we can't find it.

928
00:44:55.396 --> 00:44:57.366 A:middle
And it could be confusing
for the user

929
00:44:57.726 --> 00:44:59.626 A:middle
if they start the
application back up

930
00:44:59.626 --> 00:45:01.666 A:middle
and they just see this
activity view controller

931
00:45:01.666 --> 00:45:04.176 A:middle
and they're not really sure what
it was they were trying to share

932
00:45:04.176 --> 00:45:05.366 A:middle
or what they were trying to do.

933
00:45:05.536 --> 00:45:06.906 A:middle
And you can see the
image peaking

934
00:45:06.906 --> 00:45:07.906 A:middle
through a little bit here,

935
00:45:07.906 --> 00:45:09.856 A:middle
but in other cases you
might not see that.

936
00:45:10.656 --> 00:45:15.086 A:middle
So what do we do if we put the
application in the background

937
00:45:15.086 --> 00:45:17.346 A:middle
and it exits and we
start it back up?

938
00:45:18.406 --> 00:45:21.586 A:middle
So let's take a look.

939
00:45:22.146 --> 00:45:25.326 A:middle
So I did something
kind of subtle here.

940
00:45:25.536 --> 00:45:27.876 A:middle
It might not have jumped out
at you, so I'm going to replay

941
00:45:27.876 --> 00:45:29.486 A:middle
that kind of in slow motion.

942
00:45:29.946 --> 00:45:33.706 A:middle
So let's see the
application start back up,

943
00:45:34.426 --> 00:45:35.976 A:middle
now watch the transition.

944
00:45:36.516 --> 00:45:38.086 A:middle
See how it kind of faded in?

945
00:45:38.646 --> 00:45:42.426 A:middle
It's very subtle, but let's
look at it if it doesn't do it.

946
00:45:43.416 --> 00:45:45.136 A:middle
Starts up, boom.

947
00:45:45.796 --> 00:45:48.326 A:middle
Kind of jarring,
kind of disjoint.

948
00:45:48.566 --> 00:45:49.336 A:middle
See it again.

949
00:45:49.926 --> 00:45:54.156 A:middle
So that's kind of unpleasant
as a user, and let's look

950
00:45:54.156 --> 00:45:56.126 A:middle
at what we do regular speed.

951
00:45:56.766 --> 00:46:00.346 A:middle
Nice. It just kind
of fades right there.

952
00:46:00.646 --> 00:46:03.656 A:middle
So at least we're not
slapping the user's attention

953
00:46:03.656 --> 00:46:04.366 A:middle
around with this.

954
00:46:05.106 --> 00:46:07.726 A:middle
So that shows a few
different things.

955
00:46:08.176 --> 00:46:10.706 A:middle
Already in the previous
demos that I did,

956
00:46:10.946 --> 00:46:14.066 A:middle
you saw us using the Snapshot,
so that covers the first part.

957
00:46:14.116 --> 00:46:16.676 A:middle
Now when the application
starts up in restoreState,

958
00:46:16.826 --> 00:46:18.596 A:middle
it really does look seamless.

959
00:46:18.996 --> 00:46:20.416 A:middle
You might have even
thought I'm cheating

960
00:46:20.416 --> 00:46:23.146 A:middle
and I didn't really kill the
application but I promise I did.

961
00:46:23.776 --> 00:46:24.936 A:middle
And in this example,

962
00:46:25.146 --> 00:46:28.086 A:middle
we're showing how you
both have control,

963
00:46:28.086 --> 00:46:30.796 A:middle
how we'll sometimes
implicitly notice

964
00:46:30.796 --> 00:46:33.616 A:middle
that we shouldn't use the
Snapshot, and how we'll do kind

965
00:46:33.616 --> 00:46:36.706 A:middle
of a nice transition
in these cases to sort

966
00:46:36.706 --> 00:46:38.726 A:middle
of ease the user back in.

967
00:46:39.296 --> 00:46:42.796 A:middle
So we've added a
few enhancements.

968
00:46:42.796 --> 00:46:45.046 A:middle
I'm just going to go over
them kind of briefly now.

969
00:46:46.436 --> 00:46:49.526 A:middle
We've got some keys that are
available in every coder.

970
00:46:50.346 --> 00:46:52.466 A:middle
So in the initial
implementation when we came

971
00:46:52.466 --> 00:46:55.266 A:middle
out with this last year,
an application could look

972
00:46:55.266 --> 00:46:59.976 A:middle
at the bundled version that
was used when it saved state.

973
00:47:00.536 --> 00:47:03.216 A:middle
So it could tell,
this old version

974
00:47:03.216 --> 00:47:06.046 A:middle
of the app saveState
I've changed drastically

975
00:47:06.046 --> 00:47:08.056 A:middle
so as I restore the
state I might have

976
00:47:08.086 --> 00:47:11.206 A:middle
to do some transformations,
or maybe I don't actually want

977
00:47:11.206 --> 00:47:13.666 A:middle
to restore state from this
very, very old version

978
00:47:13.666 --> 00:47:15.536 A:middle
of the app, it's just too much.

979
00:47:16.306 --> 00:47:18.326 A:middle
And that information
was available

980
00:47:18.326 --> 00:47:19.626 A:middle
in every one of the coders.

981
00:47:20.166 --> 00:47:22.546 A:middle
Most of your app might be
fine with this old state

982
00:47:22.546 --> 00:47:24.956 A:middle
but there might be one view
controller that's changed more

983
00:47:24.956 --> 00:47:26.476 A:middle
radically, so it
would look at this

984
00:47:26.476 --> 00:47:28.036 A:middle
and say, "hey, wait a minute.

985
00:47:28.226 --> 00:47:31.396 A:middle
Let me see who saved this state,
our old version of the app."

986
00:47:32.416 --> 00:47:36.226 A:middle
We've added a few new keys that
accomplish very similar things.

987
00:47:36.396 --> 00:47:38.466 A:middle
The first one is to tell
you the system version.

988
00:47:39.626 --> 00:47:43.086 A:middle
You may have noticed iOS 7
changed a little bit from iOS 6,

989
00:47:43.576 --> 00:47:45.656 A:middle
so your app might
need to adjust metrics

990
00:47:45.656 --> 00:47:47.926 A:middle
or do something different
when it's restoring state,

991
00:47:47.926 --> 00:47:51.146 A:middle
so you can tell what version
it ran on when it saved state.

992
00:47:51.876 --> 00:47:55.066 A:middle
Also, we put the time stamp
from when we saved state.

993
00:47:55.376 --> 00:47:58.206 A:middle
This was a very common
request, as it's so useful.

994
00:47:59.006 --> 00:48:02.846 A:middle
In some cases, after an app's
been inactive for awhile,

995
00:48:02.846 --> 00:48:03.876 A:middle
you might actually want

996
00:48:03.876 --> 00:48:05.826 A:middle
to restore something a
little bit different.

997
00:48:05.826 --> 00:48:07.676 A:middle
You might want to go
back up to the beginning.

998
00:48:08.536 --> 00:48:11.626 A:middle
Because it might be confusing
to the user if they dig way,

999
00:48:11.626 --> 00:48:14.146 A:middle
way down in the app
and then a month later,

1000
00:48:14.146 --> 00:48:16.496 A:middle
when they run it again,
it goes to something

1001
00:48:16.496 --> 00:48:18.266 A:middle
that doesn't even make
any sense anymore,

1002
00:48:18.266 --> 00:48:19.756 A:middle
something that's
no longer relevant.

1003
00:48:20.296 --> 00:48:23.066 A:middle
So you'll want to take
maybe a little bit of notice

1004
00:48:23.066 --> 00:48:25.456 A:middle
of what time or the date
that this was saved.

1005
00:48:26.056 --> 00:48:31.266 A:middle
It made it easier to
handle static table views

1006
00:48:31.266 --> 00:48:32.776 A:middle
where their content
doesn't change.

1007
00:48:34.036 --> 00:48:36.876 A:middle
Now, because a table view
can have dynamic content,

1008
00:48:37.406 --> 00:48:41.436 A:middle
in the first release of
this, when we saved state

1009
00:48:41.436 --> 00:48:45.446 A:middle
and we wanted to keep track of
selected cells and the top cell

1010
00:48:45.446 --> 00:48:46.416 A:middle
that you were scrolled to,

1011
00:48:46.806 --> 00:48:49.666 A:middle
we would actually ask the data
source for the table view,

1012
00:48:50.786 --> 00:48:55.176 A:middle
what is an identifier for this
cell that makes sense to you?

1013
00:48:55.586 --> 00:48:58.696 A:middle
The reason we did that
was because the cell

1014
00:48:58.736 --> 00:49:02.806 A:middle
at index 3 today may not be
the cell at index 3 tomorrow.

1015
00:49:02.806 --> 00:49:06.286 A:middle
It may not even be the cell at
index 3 in 5 minutes or an hour.

1016
00:49:06.906 --> 00:49:09.546 A:middle
So we don't want to just
select something based

1017
00:49:09.546 --> 00:49:12.226 A:middle
on its index path if
that data could change.

1018
00:49:12.606 --> 00:49:15.936 A:middle
So we would ask the data source,
who knows all about the data,

1019
00:49:16.516 --> 00:49:19.116 A:middle
to give us some identifier,
which we would save instead

1020
00:49:19.116 --> 00:49:20.716 A:middle
of just the index path.

1021
00:49:21.486 --> 00:49:25.826 A:middle
And when we restored state,
we would then do the converse

1022
00:49:25.826 --> 00:49:28.866 A:middle
and say, "here's an identifier;
where's the index path now?"

1023
00:49:29.486 --> 00:49:31.976 A:middle
And that works out great,
especially if you have something

1024
00:49:31.976 --> 00:49:36.046 A:middle
like music or photos or a set
of articles that could be moving

1025
00:49:36.046 --> 00:49:38.286 A:middle
around and getting
sorted and changed

1026
00:49:38.286 --> 00:49:40.096 A:middle
with things getting
deleted and added.

1027
00:49:40.816 --> 00:49:43.426 A:middle
However, it's also pretty
common to use table view

1028
00:49:43.646 --> 00:49:45.066 A:middle
for a static set of things,

1029
00:49:45.066 --> 00:49:46.836 A:middle
maybe some switches
that you have.

1030
00:49:47.266 --> 00:49:49.216 A:middle
Maybe that inspector
I have there might end

1031
00:49:49.216 --> 00:49:50.546 A:middle
up with a fancy table view

1032
00:49:50.546 --> 00:49:51.966 A:middle
with a whole bunch
of different items.

1033
00:49:52.236 --> 00:49:54.196 A:middle
And it's kind of a
lot of work to have

1034
00:49:54.196 --> 00:49:57.406 A:middle
to convert these index
paths into some identifier

1035
00:49:57.406 --> 00:49:59.436 A:middle
that you contrive
and convert it back

1036
00:49:59.436 --> 00:50:00.576 A:middle
when they're never
going to move.

1037
00:50:01.326 --> 00:50:04.916 A:middle
So now, if your data source
doesn't implement the protocol

1038
00:50:04.916 --> 00:50:08.486 A:middle
we detect to ask this
question, we'll just go

1039
00:50:08.486 --> 00:50:10.216 A:middle
and save the index
path directly,

1040
00:50:10.326 --> 00:50:11.536 A:middle
and it can be really useful.

1041
00:50:12.646 --> 00:50:17.686 A:middle
And speaking of selected and
scrolled, we now added support

1042
00:50:17.686 --> 00:50:18.886 A:middle
to UI collection view.

1043
00:50:19.176 --> 00:50:22.196 A:middle
We'll remember all the selected
cells in a collection view

1044
00:50:22.276 --> 00:50:23.926 A:middle
and also of the scroll position.

1045
00:50:24.316 --> 00:50:26.056 A:middle
And you actually saw
that in the demo,

1046
00:50:26.386 --> 00:50:27.816 A:middle
so we do that all for free.

1047
00:50:28.616 --> 00:50:33.286 A:middle
And then finally, one thing that
can be extremely frustrating

1048
00:50:33.286 --> 00:50:36.066 A:middle
to a user is when
they're composing mail.

1049
00:50:36.066 --> 00:50:38.716 A:middle
Let's say that you find
a really awesome image

1050
00:50:38.976 --> 00:50:41.266 A:middle
or an interesting article
and you want to share it,

1051
00:50:41.476 --> 00:50:44.126 A:middle
so you bring up the activity
sheet as I showed before,

1052
00:50:44.446 --> 00:50:46.576 A:middle
and continue all
the way to mail.

1053
00:50:46.806 --> 00:50:47.676 A:middle
So now you're not

1054
00:50:47.676 --> 00:50:49.646 A:middle
in the activity view
controller anymore.

1055
00:50:49.896 --> 00:50:52.146 A:middle
That's gone, you're now actually

1056
00:50:52.146 --> 00:50:54.216 A:middle
in a mail composition
controller.

1057
00:50:54.696 --> 00:50:56.546 A:middle
And you type this
elaborate message,

1058
00:50:57.006 --> 00:50:59.836 A:middle
put the app in the background
for whatever reason, it exits,

1059
00:51:00.366 --> 00:51:02.506 A:middle
start it back up -- oh, no.

1060
00:51:02.906 --> 00:51:05.786 A:middle
Gone. So we thought that
was a really important thing

1061
00:51:05.786 --> 00:51:09.316 A:middle
to keep track of for users as
mail can be fairly lengthy.

1062
00:51:09.446 --> 00:51:12.726 A:middle
So if you have an
activity view controller

1063
00:51:12.726 --> 00:51:16.426 A:middle
and you give it a restoration
identifier, we'll keep track

1064
00:51:16.426 --> 00:51:18.686 A:middle
of mail drafts and
we'll save them

1065
00:51:18.686 --> 00:51:21.226 A:middle
and we'll bring the user
right back and restore them.

1066
00:51:21.746 --> 00:51:25.056 A:middle
And over time we plan to
add more to this as well

1067
00:51:25.056 --> 00:51:27.956 A:middle
so that we'll start saving more
and more specific activities,

1068
00:51:28.116 --> 00:51:30.276 A:middle
but we thought mail was
the best place to start.

1069
00:51:36.376 --> 00:51:40.286 A:middle
So I just want to take a moment
to talk about security and how

1070
00:51:40.286 --> 00:51:41.956 A:middle
that relates to state
restoration.

1071
00:51:43.726 --> 00:51:47.816 A:middle
We actually use data protection
on the archive itself.

1072
00:51:48.676 --> 00:51:52.926 A:middle
So the state restoration archive
that's saved is not accessible

1073
00:51:52.926 --> 00:51:54.136 A:middle
when the device is locked.

1074
00:51:55.376 --> 00:51:58.476 A:middle
It's an encrypted file, and
if the device is locked,

1075
00:51:58.476 --> 00:52:01.026 A:middle
even if somebody stole your
phone, managed to break

1076
00:52:01.026 --> 00:52:02.996 A:middle
into the file system
and pulled that off,

1077
00:52:03.246 --> 00:52:06.476 A:middle
they wouldn't be
able to look at it.

1078
00:52:06.476 --> 00:52:07.806 A:middle
So why do we do that?

1079
00:52:08.256 --> 00:52:11.176 A:middle
Why is it important
to protect this file?

1080
00:52:11.486 --> 00:52:12.716 A:middle
Well, there's a few reasons.

1081
00:52:13.136 --> 00:52:16.906 A:middle
One is it's really easy to
leak sensitive information

1082
00:52:16.906 --> 00:52:17.526 A:middle
by mistake.

1083
00:52:18.746 --> 00:52:20.846 A:middle
You might keep track
of the scroll position,

1084
00:52:21.766 --> 00:52:23.176 A:middle
which could inform somebody

1085
00:52:23.176 --> 00:52:25.156 A:middle
who really knows what
the app's all about,

1086
00:52:25.586 --> 00:52:28.586 A:middle
how many entries you have
and how you've been using it.

1087
00:52:29.086 --> 00:52:31.536 A:middle
There might be identifiers
that you use for some

1088
00:52:31.536 --> 00:52:33.656 A:middle
of your view controllers
or some of these objects

1089
00:52:33.976 --> 00:52:36.216 A:middle
that actually give away a
little bit of information

1090
00:52:36.216 --> 00:52:38.066 A:middle
about what a user is
doing with the app,

1091
00:52:38.276 --> 00:52:41.136 A:middle
and for some business apps
or sensitive personal apps,

1092
00:52:41.486 --> 00:52:43.516 A:middle
you might not want
anybody to know about this.

1093
00:52:43.846 --> 00:52:45.786 A:middle
You might be adding
a new contact

1094
00:52:45.786 --> 00:52:48.326 A:middle
and it's not saved
completely, but you're adding

1095
00:52:48.326 --> 00:52:50.056 A:middle
in someone's personal
information;

1096
00:52:50.296 --> 00:52:52.046 A:middle
you want that to
be kept private.

1097
00:52:52.916 --> 00:52:57.576 A:middle
Also, your application already
may be keeping things private.

1098
00:52:57.576 --> 00:53:01.746 A:middle
You may already be using data
protection for the application,

1099
00:53:02.156 --> 00:53:04.686 A:middle
and we don't want to be the
weak link in that chain,

1100
00:53:05.026 --> 00:53:08.616 A:middle
so we felt that it was
very important to make sure

1101
00:53:08.616 --> 00:53:11.986 A:middle
that the state restoration
archive was protected

1102
00:53:11.986 --> 00:53:13.796 A:middle
and that you didn't
have to worry about it.

1103
00:53:14.006 --> 00:53:17.186 A:middle
So the action on your part,
you don't have to do anything.

1104
00:53:17.316 --> 00:53:20.146 A:middle
You can put whatever you
want in there and not worry

1105
00:53:20.146 --> 00:53:22.866 A:middle
about anything leaking out
because we're protecting it.

1106
00:53:24.076 --> 00:53:26.466 A:middle
I'm going to come back to
that in a minute and see how

1107
00:53:26.466 --> 00:53:28.136 A:middle
that relates to this topic.

1108
00:53:29.276 --> 00:53:32.036 A:middle
So we added something
really neat on iOS 7

1109
00:53:32.296 --> 00:53:35.096 A:middle
that allows applications
to run in the background,

1110
00:53:36.206 --> 00:53:39.706 A:middle
and they can go and fetch assets
or do calculations or get ready

1111
00:53:39.706 --> 00:53:40.756 A:middle
for when the user's going

1112
00:53:40.756 --> 00:53:43.136 A:middle
to use the application,
which is pretty cool.

1113
00:53:43.606 --> 00:53:46.396 A:middle
So if we're doing some
background operation

1114
00:53:47.786 --> 00:53:50.796 A:middle
and the application
does state restoration,

1115
00:53:51.016 --> 00:53:51.916 A:middle
we want to make sure

1116
00:53:51.916 --> 00:53:53.916 A:middle
that everything comes
back predictably.

1117
00:53:54.296 --> 00:53:55.176 A:middle
So what do we do?

1118
00:53:55.666 --> 00:53:58.056 A:middle
So this is my application,
and let's say

1119
00:53:58.056 --> 00:54:00.996 A:middle
that your application just gets
started up in the background

1120
00:54:00.996 --> 00:54:03.686 A:middle
and here's my little magic wand.

1121
00:54:04.316 --> 00:54:07.546 A:middle
So your application just
ran unbeknownst to the user,

1122
00:54:07.756 --> 00:54:10.716 A:middle
did its thing, and since
it participates the state

1123
00:54:10.716 --> 00:54:14.566 A:middle
restoration and since the device
unlocked, when it starts up,

1124
00:54:14.566 --> 00:54:17.366 A:middle
we go through the standard
state restoration flow just

1125
00:54:17.366 --> 00:54:18.356 A:middle
like we normally would.

1126
00:54:18.686 --> 00:54:21.966 A:middle
That's because the user might
take their unlocked device

1127
00:54:21.966 --> 00:54:24.696 A:middle
and switch over to your
application, and we'd want it

1128
00:54:24.696 --> 00:54:27.996 A:middle
to a restored state and be back
where the user expects it to.

1129
00:54:28.656 --> 00:54:32.716 A:middle
But what do we do if
the device is locked?

1130
00:54:33.906 --> 00:54:36.846 A:middle
Well, we can't access that
state restoration archive,

1131
00:54:37.566 --> 00:54:40.546 A:middle
so in this case we
take a simpler path.

1132
00:54:41.096 --> 00:54:44.526 A:middle
We let the application get its
work done, fetch its assets,

1133
00:54:44.826 --> 00:54:48.486 A:middle
do whatever it needs to do in
the background, but we don't try

1134
00:54:48.486 --> 00:54:51.186 A:middle
to restore state, we won't
be able to access the file

1135
00:54:51.186 --> 00:54:53.756 A:middle
and it will fail,
and very importantly,

1136
00:54:54.246 --> 00:54:57.916 A:middle
when the application finishes
running in the background,

1137
00:54:58.106 --> 00:54:59.576 A:middle
we won't clobber the state

1138
00:54:59.616 --> 00:55:02.526 A:middle
by saving whatever
its current state is.

1139
00:55:02.736 --> 00:55:06.216 A:middle
If the application is running
while the device is unlocked,

1140
00:55:06.216 --> 00:55:07.366 A:middle
if it runs in the background,

1141
00:55:07.636 --> 00:55:10.606 A:middle
when it completes its
background task and notifies us,

1142
00:55:10.866 --> 00:55:12.226 A:middle
we'll save state again.

1143
00:55:12.226 --> 00:55:14.826 A:middle
The application may have
changed its appearance,

1144
00:55:14.826 --> 00:55:17.886 A:middle
it may have changed some of
the behavior when it did this

1145
00:55:17.886 --> 00:55:20.746 A:middle
in the background, but
if the device is locked

1146
00:55:20.746 --> 00:55:23.836 A:middle
and it couldn't restore state in
the first place, we're not going

1147
00:55:23.836 --> 00:55:26.506 A:middle
to have it save state; in fact,
the app's just going to exit

1148
00:55:26.506 --> 00:55:27.926 A:middle
after it's all done
with its work,

1149
00:55:28.226 --> 00:55:31.896 A:middle
so that it's just getting work
done, loading those assets,

1150
00:55:32.266 --> 00:55:34.956 A:middle
but not perturbing the user,
and when they start it back

1151
00:55:34.956 --> 00:55:37.906 A:middle
up it'll go back to where
it was last time the device

1152
00:55:38.216 --> 00:55:41.256 A:middle
was unlocked.

1153
00:55:42.066 --> 00:55:45.656 A:middle
One other thing about this,
now that it's more likely

1154
00:55:45.656 --> 00:55:48.966 A:middle
or that there's more potential
for our application to run

1155
00:55:49.226 --> 00:55:52.936 A:middle
in the background, if you're
restoring state, keep in mind

1156
00:55:52.936 --> 00:55:54.266 A:middle
when you start up,

1157
00:55:54.266 --> 00:55:56.556 A:middle
the application's
data may be different

1158
00:55:57.336 --> 00:55:59.086 A:middle
and that you might want
to take that into account.

1159
00:55:59.176 --> 00:56:02.066 A:middle
And state restoration
is built around the idea

1160
00:56:02.066 --> 00:56:05.426 A:middle
that you should be able to save
state and then restore it even

1161
00:56:05.426 --> 00:56:06.936 A:middle
if all your data has changed.

1162
00:56:06.936 --> 00:56:09.496 A:middle
Many of the things I was
describing before are

1163
00:56:09.496 --> 00:56:10.686 A:middle
about that very thing.

1164
00:56:11.126 --> 00:56:16.536 A:middle
But just be sensitive
and keep it in mind.

1165
00:56:17.546 --> 00:56:20.606 A:middle
So now you've gone and
implemented state restoration,

1166
00:56:20.986 --> 00:56:21.776 A:middle
but you want to be sure

1167
00:56:21.776 --> 00:56:23.586 A:middle
that your application's
doing the right thing.

1168
00:56:24.146 --> 00:56:26.086 A:middle
So do we have any tools
that can help you?

1169
00:56:26.946 --> 00:56:30.536 A:middle
Well, one of the problems
with developing this

1170
00:56:30.536 --> 00:56:34.736 A:middle
that you might run into, the
archive itself is fairly opaque.

1171
00:56:34.736 --> 00:56:36.006 A:middle
It's not a text file.

1172
00:56:36.006 --> 00:56:37.586 A:middle
You can't just go and look at.

1173
00:56:37.906 --> 00:56:39.556 A:middle
So how do you tell
what's in there?

1174
00:56:39.986 --> 00:56:43.506 A:middle
How can you ensure that you've
actually saved what you intended

1175
00:56:43.506 --> 00:56:46.266 A:middle
to save and make sure
that we've kept track

1176
00:56:46.266 --> 00:56:48.036 A:middle
of everything that you expect?

1177
00:56:48.766 --> 00:56:52.016 A:middle
Well, we have a new tool that
we're going to make available

1178
00:56:52.486 --> 00:56:53.996 A:middle
from our developer support.

1179
00:56:54.396 --> 00:56:57.396 A:middle
You can run this tool and
it'll output everything that's

1180
00:56:57.396 --> 00:56:58.106 A:middle
in the archive.

1181
00:56:58.216 --> 00:57:00.456 A:middle
I'm just going to show
you a little bit of that.

1182
00:57:01.156 --> 00:57:04.466 A:middle
Kind of looks like one of those
1960s movies about computers

1183
00:57:04.526 --> 00:57:07.876 A:middle
so very textual but
very informative.

1184
00:57:08.406 --> 00:57:10.916 A:middle
So you're going to see a whole
bunch of stuff like this,

1185
00:57:10.916 --> 00:57:12.556 A:middle
and this is just kind
of the top of it.

1186
00:57:13.666 --> 00:57:16.986 A:middle
So this first tells you what
objects have restoration

1187
00:57:16.986 --> 00:57:20.196 A:middle
classes, and that's real useful
because a common problem is

1188
00:57:20.196 --> 00:57:23.556 A:middle
when you forget to set a
restoration class or you set one

1189
00:57:23.556 --> 00:57:25.376 A:middle
by mistake on something
that doesn't need it

1190
00:57:25.376 --> 00:57:26.136 A:middle
and you're wondering,

1191
00:57:26.506 --> 00:57:28.376 A:middle
either you're not
getting any objects back

1192
00:57:28.376 --> 00:57:30.316 A:middle
or you're getting two
for the price of one.

1193
00:57:30.736 --> 00:57:34.066 A:middle
So right here you can look and
see everything that we expect

1194
00:57:34.066 --> 00:57:35.626 A:middle
to use a restoration class.

1195
00:57:36.916 --> 00:57:39.886 A:middle
Also, we just have a set
of top level information.

1196
00:57:39.886 --> 00:57:42.456 A:middle
So I mentioned we keep
track of the bundle version.

1197
00:57:43.016 --> 00:57:46.236 A:middle
We also have these new keys,
when did you save your state.

1198
00:57:46.566 --> 00:57:48.826 A:middle
What was the system
version that was used

1199
00:57:48.826 --> 00:57:49.796 A:middle
when we saved the state?

1200
00:57:50.776 --> 00:57:54.256 A:middle
And then for all of the
objects that are participating,

1201
00:57:54.636 --> 00:57:56.576 A:middle
we save a bunch of
information about those.

1202
00:57:56.916 --> 00:57:58.556 A:middle
So here's our image
view controller.

1203
00:57:59.196 --> 00:58:01.926 A:middle
So you can see on the top
there highlighted in yellow,

1204
00:58:02.306 --> 00:58:05.336 A:middle
we tell you the type of object
it is, so you can kind of scan

1205
00:58:05.336 --> 00:58:07.316 A:middle
down -- very quickly
looking for view controller,

1206
00:58:07.316 --> 00:58:10.136 A:middle
view controller -- and it also
tells you the class of it,

1207
00:58:10.416 --> 00:58:12.006 A:middle
so you can look at
it and go, "hm,

1208
00:58:12.006 --> 00:58:13.526 A:middle
that's not the class I expected.

1209
00:58:13.526 --> 00:58:14.476 A:middle
How did that happen?"

1210
00:58:14.536 --> 00:58:17.056 A:middle
And you can also look
at what it saved.

1211
00:58:17.056 --> 00:58:20.166 A:middle
And this stuff is very,
very straightforward, right?

1212
00:58:20.596 --> 00:58:22.346 A:middle
We referred to our data source.

1213
00:58:22.656 --> 00:58:25.576 A:middle
Notice it says, "object
identifier proxy."

1214
00:58:25.776 --> 00:58:28.046 A:middle
That means this is a reference

1215
00:58:28.046 --> 00:58:30.126 A:middle
to an object that's
also participating

1216
00:58:30.126 --> 00:58:32.686 A:middle
in state restoration and
not an actual object.

1217
00:58:33.446 --> 00:58:36.856 A:middle
Here, I actually put my
filters into a dictionary,

1218
00:58:37.006 --> 00:58:40.016 A:middle
so this is just a textual
representation of a dictionary.

1219
00:58:40.366 --> 00:58:42.536 A:middle
So the dictionary
itself was encoded

1220
00:58:43.476 --> 00:58:46.106 A:middle
and the keys were encoded,
but you'll notice again,

1221
00:58:46.216 --> 00:58:48.696 A:middle
we're using proxies
for the actual objects,

1222
00:58:48.876 --> 00:58:50.496 A:middle
the filter objects
in the dictionary.

1223
00:58:51.006 --> 00:58:54.816 A:middle
And here's the identifier
for the image as well.

1224
00:58:55.326 --> 00:58:58.316 A:middle
So sometimes when you're
trying to diagnose issues,

1225
00:58:58.546 --> 00:59:00.296 A:middle
you can learn quite a lot simply

1226
00:59:00.296 --> 00:59:02.456 A:middle
by taking a look
at your archive.

1227
00:59:02.786 --> 00:59:06.156 A:middle
And I think it's very useful
as you're building new code

1228
00:59:06.156 --> 00:59:09.096 A:middle
and you're testing things,
to just take the time to go

1229
00:59:09.096 --> 00:59:12.886 A:middle
through here and make sure
everything you expect is in it.

1230
00:59:14.596 --> 00:59:16.716 A:middle
Now, I mentioned that
we can pull things

1231
00:59:16.716 --> 00:59:18.466 A:middle
out of the storyboard
automatically.

1232
00:59:18.886 --> 00:59:21.686 A:middle
So here I'm just showing that
we keep track of the name

1233
00:59:21.686 --> 00:59:25.426 A:middle
of the storyboard and also what
the storyboard identifier was.

1234
00:59:25.816 --> 00:59:27.776 A:middle
And that might be
useful to you as well,

1235
00:59:27.776 --> 00:59:29.866 A:middle
even if you're not
depending on this behavior,

1236
00:59:30.266 --> 00:59:32.586 A:middle
just so that it helps
you to triangulate

1237
00:59:32.586 --> 00:59:34.816 A:middle
on what this object actually is.

1238
00:59:34.926 --> 00:59:37.116 A:middle
You're not going to have a
picture of the view controller

1239
00:59:37.116 --> 00:59:39.386 A:middle
on the right as I'm showing
here; you're just going

1240
00:59:39.386 --> 00:59:41.446 A:middle
to be looking at text
and you might think,

1241
00:59:41.446 --> 00:59:42.886 A:middle
what is this thing
I'm looking at?

1242
00:59:43.066 --> 00:59:44.766 A:middle
Oh, came out of the storyboard.

1243
00:59:45.266 --> 00:59:45.726 A:middle
There we go.

1244
00:59:46.496 --> 00:59:49.426 A:middle
Okay. How about these
generalized objects?

1245
00:59:49.786 --> 00:59:51.296 A:middle
Again, we do the same thing.

1246
00:59:51.296 --> 00:59:54.426 A:middle
We're showing that it's
just a general object,

1247
00:59:54.426 --> 00:59:56.956 A:middle
it says restorable object
-- that's my terminology.

1248
00:59:57.556 --> 01:00:01.036 A:middle
We show the class of it, and
it saved a couple things,

1249
01:00:01.156 --> 01:00:02.796 A:middle
so we just keep track
of all of that.

1250
01:00:03.186 --> 01:00:06.436 A:middle
So pretty dry, but I think
it's very interesting

1251
01:00:06.596 --> 01:00:07.646 A:middle
when you see all of this.

1252
01:00:08.336 --> 01:00:09.996 A:middle
Okay, I'm kind of
running out of time,

1253
01:00:09.996 --> 01:00:11.496 A:middle
but I have a couple more things.

1254
01:00:11.876 --> 01:00:14.706 A:middle
We've added a profile
you can install

1255
01:00:14.706 --> 01:00:17.036 A:middle
and we'll log a little
bit of extra information.

1256
01:00:17.406 --> 01:00:19.636 A:middle
You can also set a
default for the simulator.

1257
01:00:19.826 --> 01:00:23.576 A:middle
So you get kind of a play
by play in Xcode's console

1258
01:00:23.576 --> 01:00:25.916 A:middle
as your app is saving
state and restoring it,

1259
01:00:25.916 --> 01:00:28.266 A:middle
and it could be pretty
useful to look at that, too.

1260
01:00:28.886 --> 01:00:32.686 A:middle
And we have a profile that
you can install that puts you

1261
01:00:32.686 --> 01:00:34.046 A:middle
